% ── Abstract ────────────────────────────────────────────────
\begin{abstract}
Spur gears are critical mechanical components in
automotive and industrial systems, and undetected defects in
these components can lead to catastrophic machinery failures,
safety hazards, and significant production losses. Traditional
manual inspection methods are slow, error-prone, and not scal
able to high-throughput manufacturing environments. This paper
presents an automated multi-view machine vision
system for spur gear defect detection that employs a conveyor
belt, a robotic arm for automated gear flipping, and a dual
camera setup to capture four distinct views per gear. Three
state-of-the-art deep learning models—YOLOv8, YOLOv11, and
Faster R-CNN—were trained and comparatively evaluated on a
custom dataset of 1037 real-captured spur gear images annotated
for binary defect classification (Accepted/Rejected). Experimental
results demonstrate that YOLOv8 achieves the best overall
performance with a mean Average Precision (mAP) of 97.31%,
precision of 94.98%, and recall of 97.04%. YOLOv11 offers
the fastest inference at 14.4ms per image, while Faster R
CNN exhibits the lowest throughput at 9.86FPS. The complete
system is deployed through a web-based graphical user interface
that enables real-time four-view inspection and delivers a clear
Accept/Reject verdict per gear inspection cycle.
Index Terms—Spur Gear, Defect Detection, YOLOv8,
YOLOv11, Faster R-CNN, Machine Vision, Multi-View Inspec
tion, Deep Learning, Object Detection, Conveyor Inspection.
\end{abstract}

