\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}

Spur gears are among the most fundamental and widely deployed
mechanical transmission elements in automotive, aerospace, and
industrial machinery. They transfer torque between parallel shafts
and are present in gearboxes, engines, conveyor drives, and
precision instruments. The integrity of spur gears is therefore
paramount: even minor surface defects such as pitting, tooth
breakage, spalling, cracks, or wear can propagate rapidly under
cyclic loading, leading to gear failure, machine downtime, and,
in safety-critical applications, injury to operators. In automotive
manufacturing, gear defects that escape the production line can
trigger costly recalls, warranty claims, and reputational damage.

Historically, gear quality assurance has relied on manual visual
inspection, wherein trained technicians examine individual gears
under illuminated conditions and either accept or reject them
based on visual cues. This approach is inherently limited by human
fatigue, subjectivity, and throughput constraints. An experienced
inspector can typically examine only a few hundred gears per shift,
and subtle sub-surface or edge defects often escape detection
entirely. As production volumes increase and component tolerances
tighten, manual inspection has become a critical bottleneck that
does not scale economically \cite{haobo2024}.

Computer vision has been explored as an alternative since the early
1990s, but classical image-processing pipelines based on
hand-crafted features (edge detection, morphological operations,
template matching) suffer from sensitivity to lighting variation,
surface finish differences, and background clutter
\cite{tabernik2019, lv2020}. More recently, deep convolutional
neural networks (CNNs) have demonstrated remarkable capability in
detecting and localising surface defects in industrial settings
\cite{ilani2025, katiyar2021}. Object detection architectures
such as Faster R-CNN \cite{ren2015}, YOLO \cite{redmon2016}, and
SSD \cite{liu2016ssd} allow simultaneous classification and
bounding-box localisation in a single forward pass, making them
attractive for real-time inspection \cite{yolov8wd2025, mpayolo2025}.

A key limitation of most prior inspection systems is their
reliance on a single camera angle. Gears are three-dimensional
objects, and defects located on the tooth flanks, bottom face, or
side surfaces may be entirely occluded from a top-view camera.
Katiyar~et~al.~\cite{katiyar2021} proposed an automated defect
detection approach using MobileNet-SSD on physical component
surfaces and achieved 95\% precision in a single-view configuration.
However, their system could not capture hidden or under-side defects.
This motivates the design of a multi-view inspection pipeline that
systematically examines all exposed surfaces of the gear
\cite{multiview3d}.

This paper presents an automated multi-view machine
vision system for spur gear defect detection. The proposed hardware
pipeline places each gear on a conveyor-fed inspection platform where
two cameras simultaneously capture a top view and a side view. A
robotic arm then automatically flips the gear, and the same two
cameras capture the bottom view and the opposite side view,
yielding four images per gear \cite{smartinspection2023}. All four
images are processed by a trained detection model, and a final binary
verdict---\textit{Accepted} or \textit{Rejected}---is issued.
Results are displayed on the CASTVISION web-based graphical user
interface (GUI).

Three detection models are trained and compared on the same custom
dataset: \textbf{YOLOv8} \cite{yolov8}, \textbf{YOLOv11}
\cite{yolov11}, and \textbf{Faster R-CNN} \cite{ren2015}. These
architectures span a range of design philosophies---single-stage
anchor-free, latest-generation attention-augmented single-stage, and
two-stage region-proposal-based---providing a thorough comparative
benchmark for the binary gear defect detection task. Recent work has
demonstrated the effectiveness of improved YOLO architectures for
surface defect detection on industrial components \cite{sun2026,
yolo11defect2025}, and this study extends those results to the
specific domain of spur gear inspection under a multi-view framework.

The key contributions of this work are:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item A custom, domain-specific dataset of 1037 real-captured spur
        gear images with manual bounding-box annotations for binary
        defect classification (Accepted/Rejected).
  \item A multi-view four-camera hardware pipeline incorporating a
        robotic arm for automated gear flipping, enabling inspection
        of all gear surfaces.
  \item A rigorous comparative study of YOLOv8, YOLOv11, and Faster
        R-CNN on the custom dataset, reporting mAP, precision, recall,
        F1-score, FPS, inference latency, and model size.
  \item A deployed web application, CASTVISION, providing a
        user-friendly four-view gear inspection interface with
        real-time Accept/Reject verdicts.
\end{enumerate}

The remainder of this paper is organised as follows.
Section~\ref{sec:lit} reviews related work.
Section~\ref{sec:method} describes the proposed system and
experimental methodology. Section~\ref{sec:results} presents and
discusses the results. Section~\ref{sec:conclusion} concludes the
paper and outlines future directions.

