\section{Literature Review}
\label{sec:lit}

\subsection{Traditional Defect Detection Methods}

Early automated inspection systems relied on classical image
processing techniques. Canny and Sobel edge detectors, Hough
transforms, and morphological operations were combined with
rule-based classifiers to flag surface anomalies \cite{tabernik2019}.
While computationally lightweight, such pipelines required careful
parameter tuning for each specific defect type and were brittle
under illumination changes or surface finish variation. Texture
analysis methods---co-occurrence matrices, Gabor filters, and local
binary patterns---provided some robustness but struggled with the
irregular and multi-scale nature of gear tooth defects. Mery and
Berti \cite{visual_inspection_survey} studied automatic detection of
welding defects using texture features and highlighted how classical
techniques plateau in performance without structural adaptation.
Manual visual inspection, as discussed in Section~\ref{sec:intro},
remained the industrial standard primarily because these classical
methods could not reliably generalise across gear types and defect
morphologies \cite{lv2020}.

\subsection{CNN-Based Defect Detection}

The advent of deep CNNs transformed industrial defect detection.
AlexNet \cite{alexnet} demonstrated that large CNNs trained on
ImageNet \cite{imagenet} features could generalise to recognition
tasks far beyond their training distribution. Subsequent
architectures---VGGNet \cite{vggnet} and ResNet \cite{resnet}---pushed
classification accuracy on benchmark datasets and became the standard
backbone encoders for downstream detection tasks. Transfer learning
from ImageNet-pretrained weights was shown to substantially reduce
the labelled data required for industrial inspection
\cite{transfer_learning}, an important property given the cost of
annotating defect datasets.

Ilani and Banad \cite{ilani2025} applied CNN-based models to
industrial surface defect detection and demonstrated strong
generalisation to unseen defect classes. Tabernik~et~al.
\cite{tabernik2019} introduced a segmentation-based deep learning
approach on the DAGM surface defect dataset, achieving approximately
97\% detection accuracy by combining pixel-level segmentation with
classification heads. Zhang~et~al. \cite{zhang2021inspection}
proposed deep learning-based visual inspection specifically for
surface defect detection in industrial manufacturing contexts and
demonstrated that attention-guided networks improve recall on
fine-grained defect patterns. Haobo \cite{haobo2024} provided a
comprehensive survey of industrial surface defect detection methods
based on deep learning, establishing benchmarks across multiple
defect categories.

\subsection{Object Detection Architectures}

Quality control review surveys \cite{dl_quality_review} have
consistently identified three core challenges in industrial defect
detection: class imbalance between defect-free and defective samples,
high intra-class variability in defect appearance, and limited
annotated industrial datasets. Our work directly addresses the third
challenge by constructing a custom spur gear dataset.

The two dominant paradigms in object detection are two-stage and
single-stage detectors. Girshick~et~al. introduced the R-CNN family:
R-CNN extracted region proposals using selective search; Fast R-CNN
\cite{fastrcnn} introduced RoI pooling to share convolution across
proposals; and Faster R-CNN \cite{ren2015} replaced selective search
with a learnable Region Proposal Network (RPN), achieving near
real-time performance at high accuracy on the COCO \cite{coco} and
PASCAL VOC \cite{pascalvoc} benchmarks.

Single-stage detectors sacrifice some accuracy for speed. Redmon
et~al. introduced YOLO (You Only Look Once) \cite{redmon2016},
which reformulated detection as a single regression problem over a
grid. Subsequent versions---YOLOv4 \cite{yolov4} and
YOLOv8 \cite{yolov8}---progressively improved backbone design, neck
architecture, and training strategies. YOLOv8 introduced an
anchor-free detection head and decoupled classification/regression
branches, yielding superior mAP--speed trade-offs on standard
benchmarks. The most recent YOLOv11 \cite{yolov11} incorporates
C3k2 convolutional blocks and attention mechanisms for further
efficiency gains. Sun~et~al. \cite{sun2026} proposed an improved
YOLOv8s specifically for parts surface defect detection and achieved
competitive performance, reinforcing the applicability of the YOLO
family to industrial inspection tasks. Liu~et~al. \cite{liu2016ssd}
proposed SSD, which predicts at multiple feature map scales;
MobileNet \cite{mobilenet}, a lightweight backbone for mobile
applications, was combined with SSD to form MobileNet-SSD, which
was adopted by Katiyar~et~al. \cite{katiyar2021} for their
component defect detection system.

\subsection{Surface and Gear Defect Detection}

Lv~et~al. \cite{lv2020} constructed a benchmark dataset for deep
metallic surface defect detection and evaluated multiple CNN
architectures, establishing that multi-scale feature fusion
significantly improves recall on small defects. Liu~et~al.
\cite{liu2021steel} developed a real-time steel surface defect
detection system using deep learning and validated it in industrial
deployment scenarios, achieving consistent detection at line speed.
Ren~et~al. \cite{yolov8wd2025} applied a customised YOLOv8-WD
architecture for detecting defects in automotive brake joint laser
welds, demonstrating the transferability of YOLO-based models to
metallic automotive component inspection. Zhou and Zhao
\cite{mpayolo2025} proposed MPA-YOLO, an improved YOLOv8 framework
for steel surface defect detection that incorporates multi-path
attention modules for improved small-defect localisation.

For gear-specific defects, vibration signal analysis combined with
machine learning has been explored \cite{gear_fault}, though such
approaches require physical sensor installation and cannot detect
surface-visible defects that do not yet produce measurable vibration
signatures. Visual inspection therefore remains complementary to
vibration-based methods. A surface defect detection method for
electronic products based on improved YOLOv11 \cite{yolo11defect2025}
has also been reported, demonstrating accuracy improvements through
attention and multi-scale fusion within the latest YOLO generation.

\subsection{Multi-View Inspection Systems}

Single-camera inspection systems are fundamentally limited to the
visible surface area at the time of capture. Multi-view approaches
address this by fusing information from multiple viewpoints.
Huang~et~al. \cite{multiview3d} proposed multi-view 3D inspection
systems for manufactured parts, demonstrating that coverage of
hidden surfaces substantially reduces escape rate for defects
located on non-principal faces. Smartinspection systems integrating
machine learning with automated hardware have been explored in
industrial conveyor-based setups \cite{smartinspection2023}, where
the automation of part handling and orientation reduces the
dependency on human operators. Low-cost industrial automation using
open-source microcontrollers for robotic arm control has been
validated as a cost-effective approach to complement machine vision
systems \cite{arduino_automation}. Our system adopts the multi-view
philosophy, using a robotic arm to flip the gear once so that all
four principal surfaces are captured by the same pair of cameras.

\subsection{Dataset and Annotation Methods}

The MVTec AD dataset \cite{mvtec} established a rigorous benchmark
for unsupervised anomaly detection across multiple industrial
textures and objects, and has been widely used to evaluate
defect detection models. The COCO dataset \cite{coco} and
PASCAL VOC \cite{pascalvoc} established benchmark annotation
standards for object detection. For domain-specific industrial
inspection, custom datasets are essential because standard
benchmarks do not contain gear images. Roboflow \cite{roboflow}
has emerged as a widely used annotation and dataset management
platform that supports multiple export formats (YOLO \texttt{.txt},
COCO JSON, Pascal VOC XML) and provides built-in augmentation
pipelines. LabelImg \cite{labelimg} is a companion tool for manual
bounding-box annotation. Data augmentation---including horizontal
flipping, rotation, scaling, brightness adjustment, and mosaic
composition---has been shown to significantly improve model
generalisation when training data is limited \cite{augmentation}.
Song~et~al. \cite{song2020} demonstrated automatic surface defect
detection with limited annotated data using strategic augmentation,
further validating our approach to dataset expansion.
