\section{Methodology}
\label{sec:method}

\subsection{System Overview}
\label{sec:sysoverview}

The inspection pipeline is designed to systematically
examine all critical surfaces of a spur gear without requiring any
manual intervention, thereby ensuring consistency and repeatability
in defect detection. The complete workflow of the system is described
as follows:

\begin{enumerate}
  \item A spur gear is initially placed on the inspection platform,
        which consists of a motorized conveyor belt that ensures
        controlled positioning and minimal vibration during image capture.

  \item {Camera~1} (top view) and {Camera~2} (side view)
        simultaneously capture high-resolution images of the gear in
        its initial orientation, ensuring that both the upper surface
        and lateral profile are clearly visible.

  \item The captured images are fed into a trained deep learning model,
        which performs defect detection by identifying surface
        irregularities such as cracks, wear, or missing teeth, and
        generates per-view detection results along with confidence scores.

  \item  A robotic arm automatically flips the gear to expose
         the underside and opposite side surface

  \item After flipping, Camera~1 (now capturing the bottom view) and
        Camera~2 (capturing the opposite side view) again acquire
        synchronized images, ensuring complete coverage of all
        geometrically relevant surfaces of the gear.

  \item These additional images are processed by the same deep learning
        model to detect any defects present on the newly exposed surfaces,
        maintaining consistency in evaluation across all views.

\item A {final verdict} is determined: \textit{Accepted} if all four views are defect-free; \textit{Rejected} if any one or more views contain a detected defect.

  \item  The verdict, per-view results, and system log are displayed
        on the {CASTVISION web interface}.
\end{enumerate}

