\subsection{Dataset Preparation}
\label{sec:dataset}

A custom dataset was created from scratch using real-captured images
of spur gear components. All images were taken under controlled
illumination in a laboratory setting to approximate industrial
inspection conditions.

\textbf{Dataset statistics:} A total of 1037 images were collected,
comprising 529 images of accepted (non-defective) gears and 508
images of rejected (defective) gears exhibiting various surface and
tooth defects. The dataset was partitioned into training (796 images),
validation (138 images), and test (103 images) splits using a
stratified random strategy.

\textbf{Annotation:} Bounding boxes around defect regions were drawn
manually using LabelImg \cite{labelimg} and verified in Roboflow
\cite{roboflow}. A key challenge encountered during annotation was
inconsistency in bounding box tightness across team members: some
annotators drew boxes with generous margins while others annotated
tightly around the defect boundary. This was resolved through a
dedicated team review session in which common annotation rules were
established and borderline annotations were re-drawn to conform to
the agreed standard.

\textbf{Format export:} Roboflow was used to automatically export
the dataset in the formats required by each model: YOLOv8 and
YOLOv11 consume annotations in YOLO \texttt{.txt} format, while
Faster R-CNN was trained with the COCO JSON format.

\textbf{Data augmentation:} To improve model generalisation and
mitigate the modest dataset size, the following augmentation
operations were applied to the training set: horizontal flip, random
rotation ($\pm15^{\circ}$), random scaling (0.9--1.1$\times$),
brightness and contrast jitter, and mosaic composition (four random
training images tiled into a single $640\times640$ input)
\cite{augmentation}. Applying an approximate $3\times$ augmentation
multiplier yields roughly 2400--3100 effective training images.
