\subsubsection{YOLOv11}
YOLOv11 \cite{yolov11} (also referred to as YOLO11 in the
Ultralytics documentation) represents the latest iteration of the
YOLO family at the time of this study. It introduces
{C3k2 blocks}---a compactified variant of the C3 module with
two inner kernels---which reduce parameter count while preserving
representational capacity. Self-attention mechanisms are
incorporated into specific stages of the backbone to capture global
context that pure convolutions miss. These architectural changes
result in a lighter and faster model compared to YOLOv8 in terms
of inference latency, though with a marginal trade-off in accuracy
on the gear dataset. Input resolution is identical at $640\times640$.
A YOLOv11-based method applied to electronic product surface defect
detection \cite{yolo11defect2025} demonstrated the effectiveness
of this generation's attention modules for fine-grained defect
localisation in noisy industrial images.

\subsubsection{Faster R-CNN}
Faster R-CNN \cite{ren2015} is a two-stage detector. In the first
stage, a {Region Proposal Network (RPN)} slides over the
shared feature map and predicts objectness scores and rough
bounding-box coordinates for anchor boxes of multiple scales and
aspect ratios. The top-$k$ proposals are then passed to the second
stage, which applies RoI (Region of Interest) pooling to extract
fixed-size feature vectors and feeds them through two fully connected
layers for final classification and bounding-box refinement. The
backbone is ResNet-50 \cite{resnet} with a Feature Pyramid Network
(FPN) for multi-scale feature extraction. The model was pretrained
on ImageNet \cite{imagenet} and fine-tuned on the gear dataset with
a shortest-edge input resolution of 800\,px.

