\subsection{Discussion}

\textbf{YOLOv8 as the recommended model.}
YOLOv8 achieves the highest mAP (97.31\%), precision (94.98\%), and
recall (97.04\%) among the three models. In a manufacturing quality
control context, \textit{recall} is arguably the most critical
metric: a low recall implies that defective gears are incorrectly
classified as accepted and pass through to the production line.
YOLOv8's recall of 97.04\% means that only $\approx$3\% of defective
gears would escape detection, a significant improvement over both
YOLOv11 (91.44\%) and Faster R-CNN (94.44\%). Its superior precision
(94.98\%) also limits false alarms that would reject non-defective
gears and reduce throughput. The F1-score of 0.960 confirms the
balanced high performance across both classes. YOLOv8 is therefore
the {recommended production model} for the CASTVISION system.

\textbf{YOLOv11 speed advantage.}
YOLOv11 achieves the lowest inference time at 14.4\,ms per image
(70.05\,FPS), approximately 1.8$\times$ faster than YOLOv8
(25.8\,ms, 38.76\,FPS). This makes YOLOv11 attractive for
high-throughput inspection lines where the camera capture rate
is the bottleneck and slightly lower detection accuracy is
acceptable. However, its mAP (71.45\%) and precision (75.87\%) are
notably lower, indicating more frequent false positives compared to
YOLOv8. This trade-off is consistent with recent literature on
YOLOv11 applied to surface defects \cite{yolo11defect2025}, which
showed similar speed gains at the cost of marginal accuracy reduction
relative to YOLOv8-class models.

\textbf{Faster R-CNN inefficiency for binary task.}
Faster R-CNN records the lowest mAP (69.67\%) and the lowest
throughput (9.86\,FPS, 101.46\,ms inference), and the largest
model size (158.07\,MB). The two-stage architecture---region
proposal generation followed by per-proposal classification---incurs
substantial computational overhead that is not justified for a binary
(two-class) detection task. Faster R-CNN is typically advantageous
when precise localisation of many small objects is required (e.g.,
dense COCO scenarios); for the simpler spur gear binary inspection
task, the overhead of the RPN constitutes an inefficiency.

\textbf{Accuracy--speed trade-off.}
Figure~\ref{fig:bar_comparison} illustrates that no single model
dominates all metrics simultaneously. YOLOv8 leads on all accuracy
metrics while YOLOv11 leads on speed. For production deployment,
the choice depends on the line throughput requirement: at conveyor
speeds below $\approx$35 gears/minute, YOLOv8 is preferred for its
higher detection reliability; above that threshold, YOLOv11 provides
adequate accuracy with comfortable throughput headroom.

\textbf{Multi-view advantage.}
By capturing four views per gear, the system eliminates
the blind spots inherent in single-camera inspection
\cite{multiview3d}. In our test set, several gears with defects
visible only on the bottom face or opposite side were correctly
rejected by the system. A hypothetical single-view system inspecting
only the top view would have missed these defects, artificially
inflating precision and recall on the subset of visible defects
while missing a meaningful fraction of actual rejects.

\textbf{Comparison with Katiyar~et~al.}
The base paper \cite{katiyar2021} achieved 95\% precision using
MobileNet-SSD on sealing surface images in a single-view setup.
Our YOLOv8 achieves comparable precision (94.98\%) on a more complex
task (three-dimensional gear components with tooth geometry) while
additionally providing multi-view coverage, bounding-box
localisation of defect regions, and a higher recall (97.04\%).
This demonstrates that the proposed system meaningfully extends the
state of the art established by \cite{katiyar2021} for the gear
inspection domain.

