\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

This paper presented an automated multi-view spur gear
defect detection system integrating a conveyor belt, dual cameras,
a robotic arm, and deep learning-based object detection. The system
captures four views per gear---top, side, bottom, and opposite
side---to ensure complete surface coverage, and delivers a binary
Accept/Reject verdict through a web-based graphical interface.

A custom dataset of 1037 real-captured spur gear images was
constructed and annotated for binary defect classification. Three
detection architectures---YOLOv8, YOLOv11, and Faster R-CNN---were
trained for 100 epochs on this dataset and evaluated on a held-out
test set. YOLOv8 emerged as the best overall model, achieving a
mean Average Precision of 97.31\%, precision of 94.98\%, and recall
of 97.04\%, making it the recommended model for production
deployment. YOLOv11 offers the fastest inference (14.4\,ms,
70.05\,FPS) and is suitable for throughput-critical lines where
slightly lower accuracy is tolerable. Faster R-CNN exhibited the
lowest throughput and accuracy among the three, confirming that
its two-stage overhead is not well-suited to the binary gear
inspection task.

\textbf{Limitations:}
(1)~The dataset is limited to a single gear type (spur gear);
generalisation to other geometries has not been validated.
(2)~Lighting variation across different industrial environments
is not fully addressed in the current dataset or training pipeline.
(3)~Defect sub-type classification (pitting, spalling, crack,
tooth breakage, wear) is not performed---the system provides only
binary Accept/Reject output.
(4)~Input validation for invalid or unrelated image uploads
(e.g., non-gear images) is not yet implemented in the web GUI.

\textbf{Future Work:}
(1)~Extend the dataset to helical gears, bevel gears, and
rack-and-pinion components.
(2)~Introduce defect sub-type classification to provide actionable
maintenance diagnostics.
(3)~Deploy the model on edge hardware (NVIDIA Jetson Nano or
Raspberry Pi) for real-time on-device inference without cloud
dependency.
(4)~Optimise the end-to-end web-to-hardware pipeline for lower
end-to-end latency.
(5)~Explore transformer-based detection architectures such as
DETR and RT-DETR for comparison.
(6)~Implement invalid input detection and graceful rejection in
the CASTVISION web GUI.

